y China treat speech as a bodily practice that is not detachable from its use in everyday experience. Firmly grounded in ideas about bodies from the early texts themselves, Geaney's interpretation offers new insights into three key themes in these texts: the notion of speakers' intentions (yi), the physical process of emulating exemplary people, and Confucius's proposal to rectify names (zhengming).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChinese languagexPhilosophyxHistory. 0aLanguage and culturezChinaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Language. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Eastern / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846862440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438468624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438468624/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles